(1443, 'Standard Socket Head Screws', '<div class="AboutBox Clear FullGenInfo PrsnttnStructure5 Show smallVerticalGutter" id="Full_3088"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span class="SecondaryLnk Prsnttn_CloseLnk">Close</span><h3 class="PrsnttnNm">About Socket Head Screws</h3><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div><div class="SubPrsnttnCntnr" style="width:797px;"><div class="SubPrsnttnGrid"><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.01"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Choosing a Head Type</span></div><div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:525px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy">Consider the shape of the hole and the clearance above the surface when selecting a head <span class="Wrd">type.</span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure3 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.02"><div><div><div><div class="floated ImgsCntnr largeHorizontalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:77px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049221792VHCL"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/shcs-standard-b01s.png?ver=1384270728" width="77" height="75" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="floated"><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:686px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#socket head shcs"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Socket</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> are the standard for high-strength <span class="Wrd">fastening.</span> They can be installed in a counterbored hole or above the <span class="Wrd">surface.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#flanged standard head socket cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Flanged</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">socket</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> distribute pressure and cover irregular holes where the screws meets the <span class="Wrd">surface.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#low-profile socket head cap screws"><span class="Wrd"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Low</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">socket</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span></span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> are about half the height of standard socket heads for use in tight <span class="Wrd">spaces.</span></p></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure3 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.03"><div><div><div><div class="floated ImgsCntnr largeHorizontalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:77px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049231793VDCF"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/shcs-flat-b01s.png?ver=1384270739" width="77" height="75" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="floated"><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:700px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#flat head socket cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Flat</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> are angled under the head and provide a flush surface when <span class="Wrd">countersunk.</span> Most are angled <span class="Wrd">82Â°,</span> but some have a shallower <span class="Wrd">100Â°</span> angle for use in thin <span class="Wrd">materials.</span> They are not recommended for high-strength <span class="Wrd">fastening.</span></p></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure3 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.04"><div><div><div><div class="floated ImgsCntnr largeHorizontalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:77px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049231793HXBH"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/shcs-button-b01s.png?ver=1384270745" width="77" height="75" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="floated"><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:700px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#button head socket cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Button</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> have a low head and provide a finished <span class="Wrd">appearance.</span> They are not recommended for high-strength <span class="Wrd">fastening.</span> <span class="Wrd"></CBNewLine><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#flange button head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Flanged</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">button</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a></span> have a built-in washer that keeps the screw head from crushing thin or soft <span class="Wrd">materials.</span></p></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.05"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Understanding Thread Size</span></div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:417px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049241791NJVN"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-understandingscrewsizes.png?ver=1384249918" width="417" height="192" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:417px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#inch socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Inch</span></a> thread sizes are specified by diameter and threads per <span class="Wrd">inch.</span> For those with a diameter smaller than <span class="Wrd"><span class="Fraction">1/4</span>",</span> diameter is indicated by a number <span class="Wrd">(e.g.,</span> <span class="Wrd">#1</span> or <span class="Wrd">No.1).</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#metric socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Metric</span></a> thread sizes are specified by diameter and <span class="Wrd">pitch.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.06"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Understanding Threading</span></div><div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.07"><div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:175px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049251791YRRM"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-threadlengths-fulls.png?ver=1384250157" width="175" height="104" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:300px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#fully threaded socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Fully</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">threaded</span></a> screws can be screwed all the way into a threaded <span class="Wrd">hole.</span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.08"><div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:167px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049251791UNGR"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-threadlengths-partials.png?ver=1384250165" width="167" height="104" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:300px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#partially threaded socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Partially</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">threaded</span></a> screws have an unthreaded portion under the head for more holding power when force is applied from the <span class="Wrd">side.</span> The unthreaded portion is stronger than the threaded portion of a <span class="Wrd">screw.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.09"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Comparing Materials by Strength and Corrosion Resistance</span></div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:512px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268428049261792QWEE"><img class="SecondaryDatTblImg GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-table2s.png?ver=1467879196" width="512" height="386" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:512px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><span class="Wrd">Use this</span> chart to compare the trade-offs between strength and corrosion resistance in different <span class="Wrd">environments.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.1"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Other Material Properties to Consider</span></div><div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:686px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#alloy steel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Alloy</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Steel</span></a> is <span class="Wrd">magnetic.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#stainless steel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Stainless</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Steel</span></a> and <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#nickel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Nickel</span></a> may be mildly <span class="Wrd">magnetic.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#brass socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Brass</span></a> and <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#bronze socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Bronze</span></