r high-strength <span class="Wrd">fastening.</span></p></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure3 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.04"><div><div><div><div class="floated ImgsCntnr largeHorizontalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:77px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268491500577574TZOP"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/shcs-button-b01s.png?ver=1384270745" width="77" height="75" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="floated"><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:700px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#button head socket cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Button</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a> have a low head and provide a finished <span class="Wrd">appearance.</span> They are not recommended for high-strength <span class="Wrd">fastening.</span> <span class="Wrd"></CBNewLine><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#flange button head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Flanged</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">button</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">heads</span></a></span> have a built-in washer that keeps the screw head from crushing thin or soft <span class="Wrd">materials.</span></p></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.05"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Understanding Thread Size</span></div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:417px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268491500587575DKDH"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-understandingscrewsizes.png?ver=1384249918" width="417" height="192" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:417px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#inch socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Inch</span></a> thread sizes are specified by diameter and threads per <span class="Wrd">inch.</span> For those with a diameter smaller than <span class="Wrd"><span class="Fraction">1/4</span>",</span> diameter is indicated by a number <span class="Wrd">(e.g.,</span> <span class="Wrd">#1</span> or <span class="Wrd">No.1).</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#metric socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Metric</span></a> thread sizes are specified by diameter and <span class="Wrd">pitch.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.06"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Understanding Threading</span></div><div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn verticalGutter" id="Sub_3088.07"><div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:175px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268491500587575RIAK"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-threadlengths-fulls.png?ver=1384250157" width="175" height="104" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:300px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#fully threaded socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Fully</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">threaded</span></a> screws can be screwed all the way into a threaded <span class="Wrd">hole.</span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.08"><div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:167px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268491500597573YYDA"><img class="GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-threadlengths-partials.png?ver=1384250165" width="167" height="104" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:300px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#partially threaded socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Partially</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">threaded</span></a> screws have an unthreaded portion under the head for more holding power when force is applied from the <span class="Wrd">side.</span> The unthreaded portion is stronger than the threaded portion of a <span class="Wrd">screw.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div class="largeVerticalGutter"><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.09"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Comparing Materials by Strength and Corrosion Resistance</span></div><div><div class="ImgsCntnr verticalGutter"><div class="horizImgs ImgGrid"><div><div class="floated GridCell ImageCell" colspan="1" style="width:512px;padding-right:0px;padding-left:0px;padding-top:0px;"><div class="ImgCaptionCntnr" id="ImgCaptionCntnr_636268491500597573YFJJ"><img class="SecondaryDatTblImg GenInfoImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/contents/gfx/small/b01-socketcapscrews-table2s.png?ver=1467879196" width="512" height="386" alt=""/></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:512px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><span class="Wrd">Use this</span> chart to compare the trade-offs between strength and corrosion resistance in different <span class="Wrd">environments.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div><div><div class="floated GridCell SubPrsnttnCell" colspan="1" style="width:797px;"><div class="PrsnttnStructure5 SubPrsnttn" id="Sub_3088.1"><div><div class="FullGenInfo_Subhead smallVerticalGutter"><span>Other Material Properties to Consider</span></div><div><div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:686px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#alloy steel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Alloy</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Steel</span></a> is <span class="Wrd">magnetic.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#stainless steel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Stainless</span><span class="EmphasizedTxt"> </span><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Steel</span></a> and <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#nickel socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Nickel</span></a> may be mildly <span class="Wrd">magnetic.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#brass socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Brass</span></a> and <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#bronze socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Bronze</span></a> are nonmagnetic and conduct <span class="Wrd">electricity.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#aluminum socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Aluminum</span></a> is extremely <span class="Wrd">lightweightâ€”</span>itâ€™s <span class="Wrd">70%</span> lighter than <span class="Wrd">steel.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy smallVerticalGutter"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#titanium socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Titanium</span></a> is prized for its high strength-to-weight <span class="Wrd">ratio.</span> Itâ€™s <span class="Wrd">40%</span> lighter than steel and comparable in strength to Grade 2 <span class="Wrd">steel.</span> </p><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#plastic socket head cap screws"><span class="EmphasizedTxt">Plastic</span></a> is nonconductive and resists chemicals and <span class="Wrd">solvents.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="clearDiv"></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'A Torx -Plus drive has more points of contact than a conventional hex drive,  allowing you to tighten these screws with less slippage or damage to the recess. ', '<div class="CpyCntnr" style="width:406px;"><p class="PrsnttnCpy verticalGutter"><span class="Wrd">A Torx</span>-Plus drive has more points of contact than a conventional hex <span class="Wrd">drive,</span> allowing you to tighten these screws with less slippage or damage to the <span class="Wrd">recess.</span> Screws are made from black-oxide alloy steel thatâ€™s stronger than Grade 8 steel and has mild corrosion resistance in dry <span class="Wrd">environments.</span> They can be used with both Torx-Plus and standard Torx tools <span class="Wrd">(see</span> <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#torx bits">Torx bits</a> and <a class="SrchLnk" title="" href="/#torx drivers">Torx keys and drivers</a><span class="Wrd">).</span> Length is measured from under the <span class="Wrd">head.</span></p><p class="PrsnttnCpy"><img class="Prsnttn_CADImg" src="https://images1.mcmaster.com/mvB/Contents/gfx/CADIconForCpy.png?ver=1452869604" width="22" height="19" alt="For technical drawings and 3-D models, click on a part number." />For technical drawings and 3-D models, click on a part number.</p></div>', '1445', 'Torx-Socket-Head-Screws', '', 'yes'),
